Obviously there are major problems with football that have been well documented. But the overall fan experience is continuously improving in spite of what we may all feel about Goodell. That was certainly on display last night. That is all.

The list could go on and on. I think our hypothetical fan who stopped watching after 1995 and who then watched last night's Super Bowl would be shocked be how different (and generally better) the game is now.
Far more competent clock and time management. This is now a mostly solved problem (Oh, hi Andy Reed).
Smaller pads and much tighter uniforms. Watching replays from the past makes it look like the players are wearing space suits.
Quarterbacks who complete over 60% of their throws.
Kickers who make most of their kicks.
Commentators who don't say things like "Holy Toledo" or "Whoa Nelly" after fairly routine touchdowns (or any other play) and who are generally fairly knowledgeable.
Skill position players who make impossible catches constantly that make Lynn Swann's Super Bowl X catches look routine. All positions - WRs, TEs, and RBs.
Coaches who freely incorporate "college tactics" like the Option or now the RPO and who now use all four downs.
Officials who are given an impossible task of parsing out sometimes byzantine rules but who are far more competent and held to a far higher standard than in the past.
Also, HD
End zone cameras that catch angles not seen in 1995. Pylon cameras that no one thought they needed but that add perspective.
On field graphics like first down markers that are so accurate and unobtrusive the announcers have stopped labeling them as "unofficial".

Let's say you watched football in the past but stopped after the 1995 season. Super Bowl 30 was your final game until you resumed yesterday. Here's what you will be pleasantly surprised to find after 22 years.
Professional football is just far better from an entertainment standpoint than it was in the past.

A. Let's set aside real concerns about football like the extreme violence which causes CTE along with many other major injuries. B. We are also setting aside the "controversy" of black athletes expressing political views
For all the hand wringing over the NFL these days, not without reason, the entertainment aspect of professional football was on full display yesterday in Super Bowl LII.
